# Cursor Rules Organization and Naming

Use domain folders to keep rule discovery simple and predictable.

## Folder Structure
- Store rules in domain folders inside `.cursor/rules` (e.g. `react`, `typescript`, `architecture`, `rules`).
- Use one clear domain per file.
- Keep cross-domain process rules in `.cursor/rules/rules`.

## Naming
- Use concise kebab-case filenames.
- Do not repeat domain prefixes that are already encoded in folder names.
- Prefer semantic names by topic (e.g. `stable-constants-and-references.mdc`, `interface-first.mdc`).

## Authoring
- Keep frontmatter complete (`description`, `globs` when needed, `alwaysApply`).
- Keep rule text concise and action-oriented.
- Add examples only when they clarify a non-obvious requirement.
- When adding, renaming, moving, or removing rules, update `.cursor/rules/README.md` in the same change.
